==English==

===Etymology===

The earliest record of the phrase ''better late than never'' comes from around 27 BC in the 4th book<ref>{{cite web |url=http://mcadams.posc.mu.edu/txt/ah/Livy/Livy04.html |title=Livy's History of Rome |accessdate=May 29, 2007 |author=Butterfield, Bruce J. |date=1996 |format=HTML | publisher=Marquette University ([http://mu.edu mu.edu]) |language=English.}}</ref> of ''[[w:Ab Urbe condita (book)|Ab Urbe condita]]'' (''History of Rome'') by [[w:Livy|Titus Livius]].

===Phrase===
'''[[better]] [[late]] than [[never]]'''

# It's better to do something late, than to never do it at all.
#*'''1996.''' Titus Livius (translation). ''Livy's History of Rome'' (in English):
#*:''Their insolence and recklessness must be opposed, and '''better late than never'''.''

